1.explore git and GitHub commands ----------------------------------------------------------------------

# ‚úÖ **GIT BASICS ‚Äî STEP BY STEP**

### **1. Set up Git**

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"      # Set username
git config --global user.email "you@email.com" # Set email
git config --list                               # View config
```

---

# ‚úÖ **START A PROJECT**

### **2. Initialize Repository**

```bash
mkdir myproject     # Create folder
cd myproject        # Enter folder
git init            # Start git repo
```

### **3. Check Status**

```bash
git status          # See untracked/modified files
```

---

# ‚úÖ **ADD & COMMIT**

### **4. Add Files**

```bash
git add file.txt    # Stage one file
git add .           # Stage all files
```

### **5. Commit**

```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"   # Save snapshot
```

---

# ‚úÖ **VIEW HISTORY**

```bash
git log                             # Detailed history
git log --oneline                   # Short history
git log --oneline --graph --all     # Tree view
```

---

# ‚úÖ **BRANCHING**

### **6. Create & Switch Branch**

```bash
git branch feature1          # Create branch
git switch feature1          # Switch to branch
```

(Old method: `git checkout -b feature1`)

### **7. Merge Branch**

```bash
git switch main              # Go to main
git merge feature1           # Merge branch into main
```

---

# ‚úÖ **REMOTE (GITHUB)**

### **8. Add Remote**

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/user/repo.git 
git branch - M main
git push - U origin main  


2. source code management on GitHub ------------------------------------------------------------------------------


# ‚úÖ **EXAM ANSWER (WRITE THIS EXACTLY)**

**Steps to practice Source Code Management using GitHub:**

1. Create a new folder and open Terminal/Command Prompt inside it.
2. Initialize Git using `git init`.
3. Create a source code file (example: `demo.txt`) and write some content.
4. Check the status using `git status`.
5. Add the file to staging using `git add .`.
6. Commit the file using `git commit -m "Initial commit"`.
7. Create a new repository on GitHub.
8. Copy the repository HTTPS URL.
9. Connect local repo to GitHub using `git remote add origin <URL>`.
10. Push the code to GitHub using `git push -u origin main`.
11. Update or modify the source code file.
12. Check the changes using `git status` and `git diff`.
13. Add updated file using `git add .`.
14. Commit the update using `git commit -m "Updated source code"`.
15. Push changes using `git push`.
16. View commit history using `git log --oneline`.

---

# ‚úÖ **PRACTICAL COMMANDS**

```bash
mkdir gitpractice
cd gitpractice

git init
echo "Hello Git" > demo.txt

git status
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/reponame.git
git push -u origin main

echo "This is an update" >> demo.txt

git status
git diff

git add .
git commit -m "Updated source code"
git push

```

3. Jenkins installation and setup . explore the environment procedure-------------------------------------------

Here is the **same simple exam-friendly format** for:

# **‚ÄúJenkins Installation and Setup ‚Äì Explore the Environment‚Äù**

Very clean. No unnecessary text. Perfect for practical exam.

---

# ‚úÖ **EXAM ANSWER (WRITE THIS EXACTLY)**

**Steps to install and set up Jenkins and explore its environment:**

1. Install Java (JDK) and verify using `java -version`.
2. Download the Jenkins installer from the official Jenkins website.
3. Install Jenkins using the installer or package manager.
4. Start the Jenkins service.
5. Open a browser and go to `http://localhost:8080`.
6. Retrieve the initial admin password from the Jenkins log or file.
7. Enter the password and continue setup.
8. Install the recommended plugins.
9. Create a new admin user and complete the setup wizard.
10. Explore the Jenkins dashboard.
11. Create a new freestyle project.
12. Configure source code repository and build steps.
13. Save the project and run the first build.
14. View build history and console output.
15. Explore Jenkins settings, plugins, and system configuration.

---

# ‚úÖ **PRACTICAL COMMANDS (TYPE THESE)**

### **1. Check Java**

```bash
java -version
```

### **2. Install Jenkins (Ubuntu example)**

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-17-jdk

wget -q -O - https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian/jenkins.io.key | sudo apt-key add -
sudo sh -c 'echo deb https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian binary/ > \
    /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list'
sudo apt update
sudo apt install jenkins
```

### **3. Start Jenkins**

```bash
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl status jenkins
```

### **4. Open Jenkins UI**

Browser URL:

```
http://localhost:8080
```

### **5. Get Initial Admin Password**

```bash
sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword
```

### **6. Install Plugins & Create Admin User**

(Follow UI instructions)

### **7. Create a Freestyle Project**

In Jenkins Dashboard:

* **New Item**
* **Freestyle Project**
* Add **Build Step** (e.g., shell command)

### **8. Run Build**

```bash
echo "Build running in Jenkins"
```

### **9. View Build History**

Inside project ‚Üí **Build History** ‚Üí **Console Output**

---

4.demonstrate continuous and development using Jenkins------------------------------------------------------------
Here is the **same simple exam-ready format** for:

# **‚ÄúDemonstrate Continuous Integration & Continuous Development using Jenkins‚Äù**

Perfect for exam/practical. No extra text.

---

# ‚úÖ **EXAM ANSWER (WRITE THIS EXACTLY)**

**Steps to demonstrate Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Development/Deployment (CD) using Jenkins:**

1. Install Jenkins and complete the initial setup.
2. Open Jenkins dashboard at `http://localhost:8080`.
3. Create a new Freestyle or Pipeline project.
4. Configure the project to connect with a GitHub repository.
5. Add repository URL under ‚ÄúSource Code Management‚Äù.
6. Enable ‚ÄúBuild Triggers‚Äù and select **GitHub webhook** or **Poll SCM**.
7. Add build steps (example: compile code, run tests, or execute a script).
8. Save the configuration.
9. Push new code to GitHub to trigger CI automatically.
10. Jenkins fetches the updated code and starts a new build.
11. Observe the build status (Success/Fail) on the Jenkins dashboard.
12. For CD, add a post-build action (e.g., deploy script or copy files to server).
13. Save and run the job again.
14. Verify that after each code update, Jenkins automatically builds and deploys the application.
15. Check build history and console output to confirm CI/CD pipeline execution.

---

# ‚úÖ **PRACTICAL STEPS & COMMANDS**

### **1. Create a GitHub Repo**

```bash
echo "print('Hello CI/CD')" > app.py
git add .
git commit -m "Initial code"
git push
```

### **2. Create Jenkins Freestyle Project**

* Go to **New Item ‚Üí Freestyle Project**
* Add GitHub repo URL

### **3. Add Build Trigger**

* **Poll SCM**

  ```
  * * * * *
  ```

  (checks every minute)

### **4. Add Build Step (Shell Command)**

```bash
echo "Running CI Build"
python3 app.py
```

### **5. Save and Build**

Click **Build Now**.

### **6. Update Code (CI Trigger)**

```bash
echo "print('Updated Code Build')" >> app.py
git add .
git commit -m "Updated code for CI"
git push
```

### **7. Jenkins Auto Build**

* Jenkins detects changes
* Starts new build
* Shows build status in dashboard

### **8. Add Deployment Step (CD Example)**

Shell command:

```bash
echo "Deploying application..."
cp app.py /var/www/html/
```

### **9. Check Build History**

* Open project ‚Üí **Build History**
* View **Console Output** for CI/CD execution


5. explore docker commands for content management----------------------------------------------------------------

Here is the **same simple, exam-ready format** for:

# **‚ÄúExplore Docker Commands for Container Management‚Äù**

Clean, short, perfect for practical & theory exam.

---

# ‚úÖ **EXAM ANSWER (WRITE THIS EXACTLY)**

**Steps to explore Docker commands for container management:**

1. Install Docker and verify installation.
2. Pull an image from Docker Hub.
3. List available images.
4. Run a container from an image.
5. List running containers.
6. Stop a running container.
7. Start a stopped container.
8. Restart a container.
9. Remove a container.
10. Remove an image.
11. Inspect container details.
12. View container logs.
13. Execute commands inside a running container.
14. Explore Docker system information and disk usage.

---

# ‚úÖ **PRACTICAL DOCKER COMMANDS**

### **1. Check Docker Installation**

```bash
docker --version
docker info
```

### **2. Pull an Image**

```bash
docker pull ubuntu
```

### **3. List Images**

```bash
docker images
```

### **4. Run a Container**

```bash
docker run -it ubuntu
```

### **5. List Running Containers**

```bash
docker ps
```

### **6. List All Containers**

```bash
docker ps -a
```

### **7. Stop a Container**

```bash
docker stop <container_id>
```

### **8. Start a Container**

```bash
docker start <container_id>
```

### **9. Restart a Container**

```bash
docker restart <container_id>
```

### **10. Remove a Container**

```bash
docker rm <container_id>
```

### **11. Remove an Image**

```bash
docker rmi ubuntu
```

### **12. View Container Logs**

```bash
docker logs <container_id>
```

### **13. Execute a Command Inside Running Container**

```bash
docker exec -it <container_id> bash
```

### **14. Inspect Container**

```bash
docker inspect <container_id>
```

### **15. Check Docker System Disk Usage**

```bash
docker system df
```

6.develop a simple containerd application using docker----------------------------------------------------------


Let‚Äôs make this super simple so you can easily write or run it during your lab or exam.
We‚Äôll create a basic containerized web app using Docker ‚Äî step-by-step with full explanation and code üëá

üß± Goal:

Create a simple Python web app (using Flask) and run it inside a Docker container.

‚öôÔ∏è Step 1: Create project folder

Open a terminal and create a folder for the project:

mkdir docker_app
cd docker_app

üìù Step 2: Create a simple web app file

Create a Python file named app.py inside the folder:

from flask import Flask

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "Hello, Docker! This app is running inside a container."

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)


‚úÖ This code starts a web server that listens on port 5000 and prints a message.

üìÑ Step 3: Create a requirements.txt file

This file lists the dependencies needed for the app:

flask

üê≥ Step 4: Create the Dockerfile

Create a file named Dockerfile (no extension) in the same folder:

# Use an official Python base image
FROM python:3.9-slim

# Set the working directory inside the container
WORKDIR /app

# Copy project files into the container
COPY . /app

# Install dependencies
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

# Expose port 5000 for web traffic
EXPOSE 5000

# Run the application
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

üöÄ Step 5: Build the Docker image

Run the following command in your terminal:

docker build -t simple-docker-app .


This will build an image named simple-docker-app.

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Step 6: Run the container

Run the image as a container:

docker run -d -p 5000:5000 simple-docker-app


‚úÖ -d runs it in background
‚úÖ -p 5000:5000 maps your local port 5000 to the container‚Äôs port 5000

üåê Step 7: Test it

Open your web browser and visit:

http://localhost:5000


You should see:

Hello, Docker! This app is running inside a container.

üßπ Step 8: Stop and remove the container (optional)

To stop:

docker ps          # get container ID
docker stop <container_id>


To remove:

docker rm <container_id>

‚úÖ Output (Browser or Terminal)

Output:

Hello, Docker! This app is running inside a container.


7. write code for a simple user registration and push the code in github-----------------------------------

Here is a **simple HTML User Registration Form** + **steps to push it to GitHub**.
Clean, exam-ready, easy.

---

# ‚úÖ **1. Simple User Registration Code (HTML)**

### üìå **registration.html**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>User Registration</title>
</head>
<body>

    <h2>Simple User Registration Form</h2>

    <form>
        <label>Name:</label><br>
        <input type="text" placeholder="Enter your name"><br><br>

        <label>Email:</label><br>
        <input type="email" placeholder="Enter your email"><br><br>

        <label>Password:</label><br>
        <input type="password" placeholder="Enter your password"><br><br>

        <button type="submit">Register</button>
    </form>

</body>
</html>
```

---

# ‚úÖ **2. Save File**

Save as **registration.html** inside a folder named **user-registration**.

---

# ‚úÖ **3. Initialize Git Repository**

```bash
mkdir user-registration
cd user-registration

git init
```

---

# ‚úÖ **4. Add the HTML File**

```bash
git add registration.html
git status
```

---

# ‚úÖ **5. Commit the File**

```bash
git commit -m "Added simple HTML user registration form"
```

---

# ‚úÖ **6. Create New GitHub Repository**

GitHub ‚Üí New Repository ‚Üí Name: **user-registration** ‚Üí Create.

Copy the repo URL (example):

```
https://github.com/yourusername/user-registration.git
```

---

# ‚úÖ **7. Add Remote Origin**

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/user-registration.git
```

---

# ‚úÖ **8. Push to GitHub**

```bash
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

---

